@node Overview
@chapter Overview

@samp{paths.el} provides a centralized registry of filesystem paths used across the Emacs configuration. Rather than scattering hard-coded paths through dozens of packages, this file defines every important directory and file location as a @code{defcustom} variable. Other packages reference these variables (e.g. @code{paths-dir-notes}, @code{paths-file-config}) instead of constructing paths themselves.

This approach has two advantages. First, it makes the configuration portable: when the filesystem layout changes (a new machine, a different Dropbox location, or a different user account), only the variables in @samp{paths.el} need updating. Second, it provides discoverability: all known directories and files are visible in one place, with their relationships made explicit through nesting (e.g. @code{paths-dir-music-tango} is defined relative to @code{paths-dir-music}, which is relative to @code{paths-dir-google-drive}).

The variables are organized into three groups: directories (@ref{Directory paths}), files (@ref{File paths}), and other identifiers (@ref{Other identifiers}).

